<DIV class=3Dpadding10>
<H1>Cryptographic Algorithm Validation Program (CAVP)</H1>
<P>The <STRONG>Cryptographic Algorithm Validation Program =
(CAVP)</STRONG>=20
encompasses validation testing for FIPS approved and NIST recommended=20
cryptographic algorithms and components of algorithms. Cryptographic =
algorithm=20
validation is a prerequisite to the Cryptographic Module Validation =
Program=20
(CMVP). The CAVP was established by NIST and the Communications Security =

Establishment Canada (CSEC) in July 1995. All of the tests under the =
CAVP are=20
handled by third-party laboratories that are accredited as Cryptographic =
and=20
Security Testing (CST) Laboratories by the National Voluntary Laboratory =

Accreditation Program (NVLAP). Vendors interested in validation testing =
of their=20
algorithm implementation may select any of the accredited =
laboratories.</P>
<H1>Cryptographic Algorithm Validation Testing Specifications</H1>
<P>Below are the algorithms for which the CAVP currently has validation =
testing.=20
Each section consists of links to the cryptographic algorithm standard, =
the=20
algorithm validation test suite specifications (the Validation System =
document),=20
the algorithm validation list, and the test vectors to informally verify =
the=20
correctness of an algorithm implementation. <BR><A id=3D01 =
name=3D01></A>
<H2 class=3Dtop>Symmetric Key</H2>
<H3>Advanced Encryption Standard (AES), Triple-DES, and Skipjack =
Algorithms</H3>
<P>Currently, there exist three FIPS-approved symmetric key algorithms =
for=20
encryption: Advanced Encryption Standard (<STRONG>AES</STRONG>),=20
<STRONG>Triple-DES</STRONG>, and <STRONG>Skipjack</STRONG>. <EM>AES is =
the=20
FIPS-Approved symmetric encryption algorithm of choice</EM>.</P>
<UL class=3Dbullets1>
  <LI><A class=3Dpdf=20
  href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/fips/fips197/fips-197.pdf"=20
  target=3D_blank>FIPS 197</A>, <EM>Advanced Encryption Standard =
(AES)</EM>,=20
  specifies the AES algorithm. </LI>
  <LI><EM>Recommendation for the Triple Data Encryption Algorithm (TDEA) =
Block=20
  Cipher</EM>, NIST <A class=3Dpdf=20
  =
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-67-Rev1/SP-800-67-=
Rev1.pdf"=20
  target=3D_blank>Special Publication 800-67</A>, January 2012. </LI>
  <LI><EM>Recommendation for Block Cipher Modes of Operation, Methods =
and=20
  Techniques</EM>, <A class=3Dpdf=20
  =
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-38a/sp800-38a.pdf"=
=20
  target=3D_blank>Special Publication 800-38A</A>, December 2001. =
Appendix E=20
  references Modes of Triple-DES. </LI>
  <LI><EM>Triple Data Encryption Algorithm Modes of Operation</EM>, ANSI =

  X9.52-1998. <STRONG>Copies of X9.52-1998 may be obtained from <A=20
  href=3D"http://www.nist.gov/nist-exit-script.cfm?http://www.x9.org/"=20
  target=3D_top>X9</A></STRONG>, a standards committee for the financial =
services=20
  industry. NIST does <STRONG>NOT</STRONG> have copies of the standard =
available=20
  for distribution. </LI>
  <LI>The <A class=3Dpdf=20
  =
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/skipjack/skipjack.=
pdf"=20
  target=3D_blank>Skipjack algorithm</A> is referenced in <A class=3Dtxt =

  href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/fips/fips185/fips185.txt"=20
  target=3D_blank>FIPS 185</A>, <EM>Escrowed Encryption Standard =
(EES)</EM>, and a=20
  complete specification is available in <EM><A class=3Dpdf=20
  =
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/skipjack/skipjack.=
pdf"=20
  target=3D_blank>SKIPJACK and KEA Algorithm Specifications</A> (Version =
2.0, 29=20
  May 1998)</EM>. </LI></UL>
<H3>Testing Requirements:</H3>
<P>Validation testing for AES, Triple-DES, and Skipjack algorithms are =
handled=20
by the Cryptographic Algorithm Validation Program's (<A=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/index.html">CAVP</A>) <A=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/testing_labs/index.html">CST =
labs</A>.</P>
<UL class=3Dbullets1>
  <LI>AES tests are described in <A class=3Dpdf=20
  href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/aes/AESAVS.pdf" =

  target=3D_blank>The Advanced Encryption Standard Algorithm Validation =
Suite=20
  (AESAVS)</A>. </LI>
  <LI>Triple-DES tests are described in NIST Special Publication <A =
class=3Dpdf=20
  href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-20/800-20.pdf"=20
  target=3D_blank>800-20</A>, <EM>Modes of Operation Validation System =
for the=20
  Triple Data Encryption Algorithm (TMOVS): Requirements and =
Procedures</EM>. An=20
  additional test, the <A class=3Dpdf=20
  =
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/des/DESMMT.pdf">Mu=
lti-block=20
  Message Text (MMT)</A>, is also required. </LI>
  <LI><STRONG>Additional testing note:</STRONG> The AES and TDES Counter =
Mode=20
  requires additional prerequisite testing of the underlying symmetric =
algorithm=20
  using any mode of operation that utilizes the forward cipher function. =
</LI>
  <LI>Skipjack tests: As of January 2011, the CAVP only validates =
Skipjack=20
  decryption implementations. Please see <A class=3Dpdf=20
  =
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-131A/sp800-131A.pd=
f"=20
  target=3D_blank>SP800-131A Transitions: Recommendation for =
Transitioning the Use=20
  of Cryptographic Algorithms and Key Lengths</A> for more information.=20
  <BR>&nbsp;<BR>The Skipjack tests for the decrypt state are described =
in NIST=20
  Special Publication <A class=3Dpdf=20
  href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-17/800-17.pdf"=20
  target=3D_blank>800-17</A>, <EM>Modes of Operation Validation System =
(MOVS):=20
  Requirements and Procedures</EM>. The validation test suite for =
Skipjack=20
  implementations using the decrypt state consists of the Modes test for =
the=20
  Decryption Process, the Variable Ciphertext Known Answer Test and the =
Variable=20
  Key Known Answer Test for the Decryption Process. Based on the =
Skipjack modes=20
  of operation implemented, SP800-17 Section 5 indicates the tests =
required to=20
  validate an implementation of the Skipjack Algorithm. =
<BR>&nbsp;<BR>(NIST=20
  Special Publication 800-17 erroneously states the Initial Permutation =
KAT for=20
  the Decryption Process is also required for Skipjack validation. This =
is not=20
  true.) </LI></UL>
<H3>Validation List:</H3>
<P>NIST maintains validation lists for <A=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/aes/aesval.html"=20
target=3D_blank>AES</A>, <A=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/des/tripledesval.h=
tml"=20
target=3D_blank>Triple-DES</A>, and <A=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/des/skipval.htm"=20
target=3D_blank>Skipjack</A>. These lists identify the algorithm =
implementations=20
which have been tested as correctly implementing the AES, Triple-DES, =
and=20
Skipjack algorithms. Points of contact and implementation descriptions =
are also=20
included. </P>
<H3>Test Vectors:</H3>
<P>The following files provide electronic versions of the vectors for =
the Known=20
Answer Test (KAT), and sample values for the Monte Carlo(MCT) test, and =
the=20
Multiblock Message (MMT) test. These values are properly formatted in =
response=20
(.rsp) files. Vendor response files should match this format exactly. =
</P>
<P>In addition, a file with intermediate results (.txt) for the Monte =
Carlo test=20
is supplied. The Monte Carlo tests consist of 400 cases. For each case, =
initial=20
values are provided, and 10,000 iterations of the desired mode of =
operation are=20
run. The output of each iteration is used as input to the next =
iteration. To aid=20
debugging, we provide the output for each of the first five (5) =
iterations of=20
the 10,000 as well as the final (10,000th) output. The intermediate =
values are=20
indented by one tab and clearly identified by use of the word=20
"Intermediate".</P>
<P>These vectors can be used to informally verify the correctness of an =
AES=20
and/or TDES algorithm implementation. The validation system documents =
(see=20
above) describe the details of the tests. </P>
<P><STRONG>NOTE, use of these vectors does not take the place of =
validation=20
