<P><A id=3D02 name=3D02></A></P>
<H2>Asymmetric Key</H2>
<H3>FIPS 186-3 Digital Signature Standard (DSS) (DSA, RSA, and ECDSA=20
algorithms)</H3>
<P>On June 10, 2009, NIST <A class=3Dpdf=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/fips/fips186-3/frn-fips_186-3.p=
df"=20
target=3D_blank>announced</A> the adoption of <A class=3Dpdf=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/fips/fips186-3/fips_186-3.pdf" =

target=3D_blank>FIPS 186-3</A>, <EM>Digital Signature Standard =
(DSS)</EM>, which=20
is a revision of FIPS 186-2. The FIPS specifies three techniques for the =

generation and verification of digital signatures: </P>
<UL class=3Dbullets1>
  <LI><STRONG>Digital Signature Algorithm (DSA),</STRONG> </LI>
  <LI><STRONG>RSA (as specified in ANSI X9.31 (RSA)), </STRONG>and </LI>
  <LI><STRONG>Elliptic Curve DSA (ECDSA; as specified in ANSI =
X9.62).</STRONG>=20
  </LI></UL>
<P>FIPS 186-3 allows the use of any random number generator (RNG) or =
random bit=20
generator (RBG) that is approved for use in FIPS 140-validated modules, =
subject=20
to the transition schedule specified in SP 800-131A. Specific references =
to SP=20
800-90 should not be considered as a requirement to use a generator =
specified in=20
SP 800-90 until such time as the use of the other generators is no =
longer=20
allowed.</P>
<P>FIPS 186-3 incorporates the following=20
changes:<BR>&nbsp;<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;<STRONG>General</STRONG>:<BR>
<UL class=3Dbullets1>
  <LI>Specifies the use of all hash functions specified provided in FIPS =
180-3,=20
  rather than just SHA-1, </LI>
  <LI>Provides requirements for obtaining assurances of domain parameter =

  validity (DSA and ECDSA only), public key validity, and private key=20
  possession, </LI>
  <LI>References SP 800-57 for guidance on key management, including the =
key=20
  sizes and security strengths to be used, </LI>
  <LI>Provides guidance on domain parameter and key pair management, =
</LI>
  <LI>Provides more guidance on the use of RNGs to generate key pairs, =
</LI>
  <LI>Provides revised primality test guidance.=20
  <BR>&nbsp;<BR><STRONG>DSA:</STRONG></LI>
  <LI>Specifies larger key sizes, </LI>
  <LI>Replaces the domain parameter generation routine with new methods, =
</LI>
  <LI>Includes explicit methods for the validation of domain=20
  parameters,<BR>&nbsp;<BR><STRONG>RSA: </STRONG></LI>
  <LI>Approves the use of both ANSI X9.31 and PKCS #1, and provides =
guidance for=20
  their use, </LI>
  <LI>Provides multiple explicit methods for the generation of key =
pairs, </LI>
  <LI>Limits the key sizes and provides criteria for the generation of =
key pairs=20
  to be used for Federal government use.<BR>&nbsp;<BR><STRONG>ECDSA:=20
  </STRONG></LI>
  <LI>Although the Recommended Elliptic Curves continue to be included =
in FIPS=20
  186-3 (as they were in FIPS 186-2), FIPS 186-3 allows the generation =
of=20
  alternative curves, using methods specified in ANS X9.62. </LI></UL>
<P>Copies of the <STRONG>ANSI X9.31</STRONG> and <STRONG>ANSI =
X9.62</STRONG>=20
standards are available from <A=20
href=3D"http://www.nist.gov/nist-exit-script.cfm?http://www.x9.org/"=20
target=3D_top>X9</A>, a standards committee accredited by the American =
National=20
Standards Institute (ANSI). NIST does NOT have copies of these standards =

available for distribution.</P>
<P>All three digital signature techniques in FIPS 186-3 make use of the =
Secure=20
Hash Algorithms specified in FIPS 180-3 dated October 2008, <EM>Secure =
Hash=20
Standard (SHS)</EM> accessible via the hashing section of this =
webpage.</P>
<P>FIPS 186-2 and FIPS 186-3 are currently the <EM>only</EM> FIPS =
standards that=20
contain Approved methods for digital signatures.</P>
<H3>Testing Requirements:</H3>
<P><A =
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/testing_labs/index.html">CST=20
labs</A> can test for conformance to the algorithm specifications in =
FIPS 186-3=20
for the DSA, ECDSA, and RSA algorithms. </P>
<P>The algorithm validation testing requirements for FIPS 186-3 DSA are=20
specified in:</P>
<P><A class=3Dpdf=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/dss2/dsa2vs.pdf"=20
target=3D_blank><STRONG>Digital Signature Algorithm Validation System=20
(DSA2VS)</STRONG></A><BR><STRONG>Additional testing note:</STRONG> For =
the=20
Domain Parameter Generation and Verification, and the Signature =
Generation and=20
Verification functions, the underlying SHA algorithm must be validated =
as part=20
of the DSA validation. In addition, Signature Generation and Key Pair =
Generation=20
require the RNG/DRBG algorithm to be validated as well.</P>
<P>The algorithm validation testing requirements for FIPS 186-3 ECDSA =
are=20
specified in:</P>
<P><A class=3Dpdf=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/dss2/ecdsa2vs.pdf"=
=20
target=3D_blank><STRONG>Elliptic Curve Digital Signature Algorithm =
Validation=20
System (ECDSA2VS)</STRONG></A><BR><STRONG>Additional testing =
note:</STRONG> As=20
part of the ECDSA validation, additional algorithms implemented by the =
ECDSA=20
algorithm must be validated. For the Key Pair Generation function, this =
includes=20
the underlying RNG/ DRBG algorithm. For the Signature Generation =
function, the=20
underlying SHA and the RNG/DRBG algorithms must be validated. For the =
Signature=20
Verification function, the underlying SHA algorithm must be =
validated.</P>
<P>The algorithm validation testing requirements for FIPS 186-3 RSA are=20
specified in:</P>
<P><A class=3Dpdf=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/dss2/rsa2vs.pdf"=20
target=3D_blank><STRONG>186-3 RSA Validation System=20
(186-3RSAVS)</STRONG></A><BR><STRONG>Additional testing note:</STRONG> =
The=20
underlying SHA algorithm must be validated as part of the 186-3 RSA =
validation=20
for all functions - Key Generation, Signature Generation, and Signature=20
Verification.. In addition, Key Generation requires the RNG/DRBG =
algorithm to be=20
validated as well.</P>
<H3>FIPS 186-2 Digital Signature Standard (DSS) (DSA, RSA, and ECDSA=20
algorithms)</H3>
<P>On February 15, 2000, NIST <A=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/dss/fr000215.html"=
=20
target=3D_blank>announced</A> the approval of <A=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/PubsFIPSArch.html"=20
target=3D_blank><EM>FIPS 186-2 with Change Notice 1 dated October 5,=20
2001</EM></A>, <EM>Digital Signature Standard (DSS)</EM>, which =
supersedes FIPS=20
186-1. This standard specifies three FIPS-approved algorithms for =
generating and=20
verifying digital signatures:</P>
<UL class=3Dbullets1>
  <LI><STRONG>Digital Signature Algorithm (DSA),</STRONG> </LI>
  <LI><STRONG>RSA (as specified in ANSI X9.31), and</STRONG> </LI>
  <LI><STRONG>Elliptic Curve DSA (ECDSA; as specified in ANSI =
X9.62).</STRONG>=20
  </LI></UL>
<P>New items in the DSS include:</P>
<UL class=3Dbullets1>
  <LI>the approval of Elliptic Curve DSA (ECDSA) as specified in ANSI =
X9.62,=20
  </LI>
  <LI>a list of recommended elliptic curves for Federal Government use =
(see=20
  Appendix 6 of <A =
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/PubsFIPSArch.html"=20
  target=3D_blank><EM>FIPS 186-2 with Change Notice 1 dated October 5,=20
  2001</EM></A>), and </LI>
  <LI>an <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/dss/fr000215.html#=
PKCS1"=20
  target=3D_blank>allowance for the continued acquisition of =
implementations of=20
  PKCS#1 for a transition period of eighteen (18) months</A>. </LI></UL>
<P>Copies of the <STRONG>ANSI X9.31</STRONG> and <STRONG>ANSI =
X9.62</STRONG>=20
standards are available from <A=20
href=3D"http://www.nist.gov/nist-exit-script.cfm?http://www.x9.org/"=20
target=3D_top>X9</A>, a standards committee accredited by the American =
National=20
Standards Institute (ANSI). NIST does NOT have copies of these standards =

available for distribution.</P>
<P>All three digital signature techniques in FIPS 186-2 (with Change =
Notice 1=20
dated October 5, 2001) make use of the Secure Hash Algorithms specified =
in FIPS=20
180-3 dated October 2008, <EM>Secure Hash Standard (SHS)</EM> accessible =
via the=20
hashing section of this webpage.</P>
<P>DSA, RSA, and ECDSA are currently the <EM>only</EM> FIPS-approved =
methods for=20
digital signatures.</P>
<H3>Testing Requirements:</H3>
<P><A =
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/testing_labs/index.html">CST=20
labs</A> can test for conformance to the algorithm specifications in =
FIPS 186-2=20
(with Change Notice 1 dated October 5, 2001). Algorithm specifications =
included=20
in this standard are the DSA, the RSA and the ECDSA algorithms. In =
addition,=20
NIST can test for conformance to two other versions of the RSA algorithm =

specified in <EM>PKCS#1 v2.1: RSA Cryptography Standard, RSA =
Laboratories, June=20
2002</EM>.</P>
<P>The testing requirements are specified in:</P>
<P><A class=3Dpdf=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/dss/DSAVS.pdf"=20
target=3D_blank><STRONG>Digital Signature Algorithm Validation System=20
(DSAVS)</STRONG></A><BR><STRONG>Additional testing note:</STRONG> For =
the Domain=20
Parameter Generation and Verification, and the Signature Generation and=20
Verification functions, the underlying SHA-1 algorithm must be validated =
as part=20
of the DSA validation.</P>
<P><A class=3Dpdf=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/dss/RSAVS.pdf"=20
target=3D_blank><STRONG>RSA Validation System=20
(RSAVS)</STRONG></A><BR><STRONG>Beginning September 28, 2006:</STRONG>=20
Validation testing for RSA algorithm implementations of the =
RSASSA-PKCS1-v1_5,=20
as specified in <EM>Public Key Cryptography Standards (PKCS) #1 v2.1: =
RSA=20
Cryptography Standard-2002</EM>, and the RSA X9.31 algorithms include =
additional=20
testing to assure the encoded message EM and the intermediate integer IR =
are in=20
the correct formats. This testing verifies that an implementation under =
test=20
(IUT) does not contain a potential implementation design that could =
introduce a=20
vulnerability in these algorithms. This testing has been added to the =
Signature=20
Verification validation test described in the RSAVS document. No =
modification to=20
this document was necessary to add this feature. Below in the Test =
Vectors=20
section, there are test vectors available to informally test if this=20
vulnerability exists in an implementation.</P>
<P>For all validated cryptographic modules that incorporate RSA, the =
CAVP and=20
CMVP strongly suggest re-testing of the RSA algorithmic implementations =
to=20
determine if the vulnerability is present.</P>
<P>If new CAVP testing is performed and the vulnerability is determined =
not to=20
be present, the CSTL can submit the new test results to the CAVP along =
with a=20
letter indicating that the implementation passed the RSA testing in =
CAVS5.2 and=20
the vulnerability is not present. The letter should request that a new =
algorithm=20
certificate be printed to replace the already issued certificate =
referencing the=20
new version of CAVS. Please indicate the already issued certificate =
number. This=20
letter should be included in the zip file along with the other files. =
Note that=20
the certificate number will not change. Only the reference to the =
version of the=20
CAVS tool and the signatory date will be changed. (Note the validation =
request=20
will be submitted using already established procedures.)</P>
<P>If CAVP testing is performed and the vulnerability is discovered, the =

following revalidation process shall be followed:</P>
<UL class=3Dbullets1>
  <LI>The algorithm implementation is changed to remove the =
vulnerability=20
  resulting in a different version number, </LI>
  <LI>Submit the new test results to the CAVP for the new version of the =

  implementation. A new algorithm certificate will be issued for the new =
version=20
  of the implementation. The certificate will reference CAVS5.2. =
</LI></UL>
<P><STRONG>Additional testing note:</STRONG> For the RSA functions, all=20
underlying SHA algorithm(s) supported by the RSA implementation must be=20
validated as part of the RSA validation.</P>
<P><A class=3Dpdf=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/dss/ECDSAVS.pdf"=20
target=3D_blank><STRONG>Elliptic Curve Digital Signature Algorithm =
(ECDSA)=20
Validation System (ECDSAVS)</STRONG></A><BR><STRONG>Additional testing=20
note:</STRONG> For the Signature Generation and Verification functions, =
the=20
underlying SHA-1 algorithm must be validated as part of the ECDSA=20
validation.</P>
<H3>Validation Listings:</H3>
<P>NIST maintains the current DSA, ECDSA, and RSA Validation Lists.</P>
<UL class=3Dbullets1>
  <LI><A =
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/dss/dsaval.htm"=20
