<H2>Deterministic Random Bit Generators (DRBG)</H2>
<P><A class=3Dpdf=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-90A/SP800-90A.pdf"=
=20
target=3D_blank><EM>SP 800-90A Recommendation for Random Number =
Generation Using=20
Deterministic Random Bit Generators</EM></A> specifies mechanisms for =
the=20
generation of random bits using deterministic methods. There are four =
mechanisms=20
discussed in this Special Publication. These mechanisms are based on =
either hash=20
functions (Hash_DRBG, HMAC_DRBG), block cipher algorithms using Counter =
mode=20
(CTR_DRBG ) or number theoretic (Dual EC_DRBG) problems. </P>
<H3>Testing Requirements:</H3>
<P>CST labs can test for conformance to the DRBG algorithms in Special=20
Publication 800-90. The testing requirements for this algorithm can be =
found in=20
the document titled <A class=3Dpdf=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/drbg/DRBGVS.pdf"=20
target=3D_blank>The DRBG Validation System (DRBGVS)</A>. =
<STRONG>Additional=20
testing note:</STRONG> Each of the mechanisms containing underlying =
algorithms=20
which must be validated as part of the DBRG validation. For HASH_DRBG, =
the SHA=20
algorithm(s) must be tested. For HMAC_DRBG, the HMAC algorithm must be =
tested.=20
For the block cipher algorithms using Counter mode CTR_DRBG, a =
NIST-Approved=20
symmetric key algorithm using Counter mode, must be validated as part of =
the=20
CMAC validation. Currently, NIST approves both the AES and TDES =
algorithms for=20
use with DRBG. For Dual EC_DRBG, the ECDSA Key Generation function and =
the SHA=20
algorithm must be tested. The ECDSA Key Generation function tests the =
point=20
multiplication function used in the Dual EC_DRBG.</P>
<H3>Validation List:</H3>
<P>NIST maintains the current <A=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/drbg/drbgval.html"=
=20
target=3D_blank>DRBG Validation List</A>.</P>
<H3>Test Vectors:</H3>
<P>DRBG Test Vectors - These files provide an electronic version of the =
test=20
vectors that can be used to informally verify the correctness of a DRBG=20
algorithm implementation using the DRBGVS. <STRONG>However, use of these =
vectors=20
does not take the place of validation obtained through the Cryptographic =

Algorithm Validation Program (CAVP). </STRONG></P>
<P><A class=3Dzip=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/drbg/drbgtestvecto=
rs.zip">DRBG=20
Test Vectors</A> DRBG Test Vectors In this zip file, there are 4 text =
files with=20
NIST SP 800-90 DRBG test vectors: <STRONG>HASH_DRBG.txt, HMAC_DRGB.txt,=20
CTR_DRBG.txt, </STRONG>and <STRONG>Dual_EC_DRBG.txt.</STRONG>. </P><A=20
class=3DtopLink href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/#top">Back =
to Top</A>=20
<P></P>
<P><A id=3D06 name=3D06></A></P>
<H2>Key Management -Key Agreement Schemes and Key Confirmation =
(KAS)</H2>
<P><A class=3Dpdf=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-56A/SP800-56A_Revi=
sion1_Mar08-2007.pdf"=20
target=3D_blank><EM>SP 800-56A Recommendation for Pair-Wise Key =
Establishment=20
Schemes Using Discrete Logarithm Cryptography (Revised March =
2007)</EM></A>=20
specifies key establishment schemes based on standards developed by the=20
Accredited Standards Committee (ASC) X9, Inc.: ANS X9.42 (Agreement of =
Symmetric=20
Keys Using Discrete Logarithm Cryptography) and ANS X9.63 (Key Agreement =
and Key=20
Transport Using Elliptic Curve Cryptography). </P>
<H3>Testing Requirements:</H3>
<P>CST labs can test for conformance to the Key Agreement Schemes (KAS) =
and Key=20
Confirmation algorithms specified in Special Publication 800-56A. The =
testing=20
requirements for this algorithm can be found in the document titled <A =
class=3Dpdf=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/keymgmt/KASVS.pdf"=
=20
target=3D_blank>The KAS Validation System (KASVS)</A>. =
<STRONG>Additional testing=20
note:</STRONG> The KAS validation process requires additional =
prerequisite=20
testing of the underlying DSA and/or ECDSA algorithm based on which type =
of=20
cryptography is supported and which underlying cryptographic functions =
are=20
supported, the supported SHA algorithm(s), supported MAC algorithm(s) =
(CCM,=20
CMAC, and/or HMAC), and the supported RNG and/or DRBG algorithm(s). (See =
CAVP=20
FAQ GEN.5 for more detailed information on prerequisites.) </P>
<H3>Validation List:</H3>
<P>NIST maintains the current <A=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/keymgmt/kasval.htm=
l"=20
target=3D_blank>KAS Validation List</A>. </P>
<H3>Test Vectors:</H3>
<P>KAS Test Vectors - These files provide an electronic version of the =
test=20
vectors that can be used to informally verify the correctness of a key =
agreement=20
scheme and key confirmation algorithm implementation using the KASVS.=20
<EM><STRONG>However, use of these vectors does not take the place of =
validation=20
obtained through the Cryptographic Algorithm Validation Program (CAVP).=20
</STRONG></EM></P>
<P><A class=3Dzip=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/keymgmt/kastestvec=
tors.zip">KAS=20
Test Vectors</A> See the KASVS document for an explanation of the =
files.</P><A=20
class=3DtopLink href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/#top">Back =
to Top</A>=20
<P><A id=3D07 name=3D07></A></P>
<H2>Message Authentication (MAC)</H2>
<H3>Block Cipher-based MAC Algorithm (CMAC)</H3>
<P>The CMAC algorithm is specified in <A class=3Dpdf=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-38B/SP_800-38B.pdf=
"=20
target=3D_blank>Special Publication 800-38B</A> dated May 2005, =
Recommendation for=20
Block Cipher Modes of Operation: The CMAC Mode for Authentication. CMAC =
can be=20
considered a mode of operation of the block cipher because it is based =
on an=20
approved symmetric key block cipher, such as the Advanced Encryption =
Standard=20
(AES) algorithm currently specified in Federal Information Processing =
Standard=20
(FIPS) Pub. 197. CMAC is also an approved mode of the Triple Data =
Encryption=20
Algorithm (TDEA). </P>
<P>NOTE: Replacement examples have been provided to correct the examples =
located=20
in the back of SP800-38B. <A class=3Dpdf=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-38B/Updated_CMAC_E=
xamples.pdf"=20
target=3D_blank>(Updated SP800-38B Examples)</A>. </P>
<H3>Testing Requirements:</H3>
<P>CST labs can test for conformance to the CMAC algorithm in Special=20
Publication 800-38B. The testing requirements for this algorithm can be =
found in=20
the document titled <A class=3Dpdf=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/mac/CMACVS.pdf"=20
target=3D_blank>The CMAC Validation System (CMACVS)</A>. =
<STRONG>Additional=20
testing note:</STRONG> The CMAC validation process requires additional=20
prerequisite testing of the underlying NIST-Approved symmetric key =
algorithm=20
using any mode of operation used by the CMAC implementation that =
utilizes the=20
forward cipher function. Currently, NIST approves both the AES and TDES=20
algorithms for use with CMAC.</P>
<H3>Validation List:</H3>
<P>NIST maintains the current CMAC Validations. CMAC Validations are =
included on=20
the validation list of its approved symmetric key block cipher -- =
therefore it=20
is included on either the <A=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/aes/aesval.html"=20
target=3D_blank>AES Validation List</A> or the <A=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/des/tripledesval.h=
tml"=20
target=3D_blank>TDES Validation List</A>.</P>
<H3>Test Vectors:</H3>
<P>CMAC Test Vectors - These files provide an electronic version of the =
test=20
vectors that can be used to informally verify the correctness of a CMAC=20
algorithm implementation using the CMACVS. <EM><STRONG>However, use of =
these=20
vectors does not take the place of validation obtained through the =
Cryptographic=20
Algorithm Validation Program (CAVP).</STRONG></EM></P>
<P><A class=3Dzip=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/mac/cmactestvector=
s.zip">CMAC=20
Test Vectors</A></P>
<H3>Counter with Cipher Block Chaining-Message Authentication Code =
(CCM)</H3>
<P>The Counter with Cipher Block Chaining-Message Authentication Code =
(CCM) is=20
specified in <A class=3Dpdf=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-38C/SP800-38C.pdf"=
=20
target=3D_blank>Special Publication 800-38C</A> dated May, 2004, Counter =
with=20
Cipher Block Chaining-Message Authentication Code (CCM). CCM is based on =
an=20
approved symmetric key block cipher algorithm whose block size is 128 =
bits, such=20
as the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) algorithm currently specified =
in=20
Federal Information Processing Standard (FIPS) Pub. 197 [2]; thus, CCM =
cannot be=20
used with the Triple Data Encryption Algorithm [3], whose block size is =
64 bits.=20
Currently the only NIST-Approved 128 bit symmetric key algorithm is =
AES.</P>
<H3>Testing Requirements:</H3>
<P>CST labs can test for conformance to the CCM algorithm in Special =
Publication=20
800-38C. The testing requirements for this algorithm can be found in the =

document titled <A class=3Dpdf=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/mac/CCMVS.pdf"=20
target=3D_blank>The Counter with Cipher Block Chaining-Message =
Authentication Code=20
(CCM) Validation System (CCMVS)</A>. <STRONG>Additional testing =
note:</STRONG>=20
The CCM validation process requires additional prerequisite testing of =
the=20
underlying NIST-Approved 128 bit symmetric key algorithm using any mode =
of=20
operation used by the CCM implementation that utilizes the forward =
cipher=20
function. Currently, the only 128 bit symmetric key algorithm approved =
by NIST=20
is AES.</P>
<H3>Validation List:</H3>
<P>NIST maintains the current CCM Validations. CCM Validations are =
included on=20
the validation list of its approved symmetric key block cipher whose =
block size=20
is 128 bits-- therefore it is included on the <A=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/aes/aesval.html"=20
target=3D_blank>AES Validation List</A>. NIST maintains the original <A=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/mac/ccmval.html"=20
target=3D_blank>CCM Validation List</A>. for historical purposes. The =
information=20
contained on the CCM Validation List has been duplicated in the AES =
Validation=20
List. </P>
<H3>Test Vectors:</H3>
<P>CCM Test Vectors - These files provide an electronic version of the =
test=20
vectors that can be used to informally verify the correctness of a CCM =
algorithm=20
implementation using the CCMVS. <EM><STRONG>However, use of these =
vectors does=20
not take the place of validation obtained through the Cryptographic =
Algorithm=20
Validation Program (CAVP).</STRONG></EM></P>
<P><A class=3Dzip=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/mac/ccmtestvectors=
.zip">CCM=20
Test Vectors</A></P>
<H3>Galois/Counter Mode (GCM) and GMAC</H3>
<P>The Galois/Counter Mode (GCM) and GMAC is specified in <A class=3Dpdf =

href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-38D/SP-800-38D.pdf=
"=20
target=3D_blank>Special Publication 800-38D</A> dated November, 2007,=20
Recommendation for Block Cipher Modes of Operation: Galois/Counter Mode =
(GCM)=20
and GMAC. GCM is based on an approved symmetric key block cipher =
algorithm whose=20
block size is 128 bits, such as the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) =
algorithm=20
currently specified in Federal Information Processing Standard (FIPS) =
Pub. 197=20
[2]; thus, GCM cannot be used with the Triple Data Encryption Algorithm =
[3],=20
whose block size is 64 bits. Currently the only NIST-Approved 128 bit =
symmetric=20
key algorithm is AES.</P>
<H3>Testing Requirements:</H3>
<P>CST labs can test for conformance to the GCM and GMAC algorithms in =
Special=20
Publication 800-38D. The testing requirements for this algorithm can be =
found in=20
the document titled <A class=3Dpdf=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/mac/gcmvs.pdf"=20
target=3D_blank>The Galois/Counter Mode (GCM) and GMAC Validation System =

(GCMVS)</A>. <STRONG>Additional testing note:</STRONG> The GCM =
validation=20
process requires additional prerequisite testing of the underlying =
NIST-Approved=20
128 bit symmetric key algorithm using any mode of operation used by the =
GCM=20
implementation that utilizes the forward cipher function. Currently, the =
only=20
128 bit symmetric key algorithm approved by NIST is AES. If the IVs are=20
generated internally, the RNG or DRBG must also be validated. </P>
<H3>Validation List:</H3>
<P>NIST maintains the current GCM Validations. GCM Validations are =
included on=20
the validation list of its approved symmetric key block cipher whose =
block size=20
is 128 bits-- therefore it is included on the <A=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/aes/aesval.html"=20
target=3D_blank>AES Validation List</A>.=20
<H3>Test Vectors:</H3>
<P>GCM Test Vectors - These files provide an electronic version of the =
test=20
vectors that can be used to informally verify the correctness of a GCM =
algorithm=20
implementation using the GCMVS. <EM><STRONG>However, use of these =
vectors does=20
not take the place of validation obtained through the Cryptographic =
Algorithm=20
Validation Program (CAVP).</STRONG></EM> </P>
<P><A class=3Dzip=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cavp/documents/mac/gcmtestvectors=
.zip"=20
target=3D_parent>GCM Test Vectors</A></P>
<H3>Keyed-Hash Message Authentication Code (HMAC)</H3>
<P>The Keyed-Hash Message Authentication Code (HMAC) is specified in <A=20
class=3Dpdf =
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/fips/fips198/fips-198a.pdf"=20
target=3D_blank>FIPS 198</A> dated March 6, 2002, Keyed-Hash Message=20
Authentication Code (HMAC). This algorithm utilizes the Secure Hash =
Algorithms=20
as an underlying primitive.</P>
